entry.title: [A11y] Fix errors when content-visibility causes node to be attached
entry.content:
Fix for test SidePanelBookmarksTest.List (browser_tests suite) when it

is run with a11y on.



Problem:

The content-visibility CSS causes a node to be attached to the layout

tree, and we update the children of the node with content-visibility.

However, even though the node has new children, it's cached

children aren't updated, leading to the serializer running into

a bad child.



Fix:

Call ChildrenChanged() when NodeIsAttached() is called with a

content-visibility subtree.



Also add an additional check to AXObjectCacheImpl::CheckTreeIsUpdated(),

so that future similar problems are flagged before they hit the

serializer.

entry.title: [gbb-cct] Improve sWAA checker
entry.content:
sWAA checker had a couple of issues in caching and providing the updated

value obtained from the server. This CL improves it:



- Persists the value to the storage first and then invokes the callback.

This was being done in the reverse order, which caused the fetched

value to be available not immediately but only from the next call

from the callers.

- Makes an additional query to server if the value is not cached or

false at the beginning. This to work around the problem that the

fetched value is often false even when it is true.

- Takes care of a situation where PIH components are created after

Tab finishes loading. Now PIH, upon creation, checks the tab

loading status to set up autotriggering as expected without missing

the event.

entry.title: Make ResourceRequestClient::OnReceivedRedirect accept a callback
entry.content:
Currently when ResourceRequestSender in the renderer process receives

a 30X redirect response, it calls ResourceRequestClient::

OnReceivedRedirect() which returns a bool value. If the returned value

is true, ResourceRequestSender follows the redirection. And if the

returned value is false, it cancels the request. This logic was

initially introduced by https://crrev.com/6568a9e3 in 2009.



This CL changes ResourceRequestSender to pass a callback

`OnceCallback removed_headers)>` to

ResourceRequestClient::OnReceivedRedirect(). When ResourceRequestClient

decides to follow the redirect, it calls the callback. If

ResourceRequestClient decides not to follow the redirect, it calls

ResourceRequestSender::Cancel() without calling the callback.



This CL is a preparation for the off the main thread resource loading

project.



* Details of this change *

ResourceRequestClient is implemented by URLLoader::Context and

SyncLoadContext.



- For handling redirects of asynchronous requests, URLLoader::Context::

OnReceivedRedirect() calls ResourceLoader::WillFollowRedirect().

- If ResourceLoader decides to follow the request,

ResourceLoader:: WillFollowRedirect returns true.

And URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() calls the

`follow_redirect_callback` synchronously.

- If ResourceLoader decides not to follow the request, it deletes the

URLLoader in HandleError(). And ResourceRequestSender::Cancel() is

called from the destructor of URLLoader. And then

ResourceLoader::WillFollowRedirect() returns false. So

URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() doesn't call the

`follow_redirect_callback`.



- The redirect handling of synchronous requests (eg:sync-XHR) is a

little bit tricky. SyncLoadContext's background thread fetching logic

was introduced by crrev.com/c/603776. And the redirect checking on the

original thread was introduced by crrev.com/c/1053237.



Here is the flow of handling synchronous requests:



* Current flow:

[Original thread] [Background thread]

RRS::SendSync() |

|=[1]=========================> SLC::StartAsyncWithWaitableEvent()

| WaitableEvent::Wait() | RRS::SendAsync() [2]

| | [IPC <==> network service]

| | SLC::OnReceivedRedirect() [3]

| | | FindClientHintsToRemove()

| | | RRS::Freeze(kStrict);

| |<=[4]========================| WaitableEvent::Signal();

| URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() [5]

| ResourceLoader::WillFollowRedirect()

|=[6]=========================> SLC::FollowRedirect() [7]

| WaitableEvent::Wait() | RRS::Freeze(kNone);

| | (Conitinues the request)



* After this CL:

[Original thread] [Background thread]

RRS::SendSync() |

|=[1]==========================> SLC::StartAsyncWithWaitableEvent()

| WaitableEvent::Wait() | RRS::SendAsync() [2]

| | [IPC <==> network service]

| | SLC::OnReceivedRedirect() [3]

| |<=[4]========================| WaitableEvent::Signal();

| URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() [5]

| ResourceLoader::WillFollowRedirect()

| FindClientHintsToRemove()

| Run follow_redirect_callback

|=[6]=========================> SLC::FollowRedirect() [7]

| WaitableEvent::Wait() | Run follow_redirect_callback_

| | (Conitinues the request)



RRS: ResourceRequestSender

RRC: ResourceRequestClient

SLC: SyncLoadContext



The current flow is like this:

- In the original thread:

[1] ResourceRequestSender::SendSync() post a task to a background

thread to call SyncLoadContext::StartAsyncWithWaitableEvent()

- In the background thread:

[2] ResourceRequestSender::SendAsync() starts the request.

[3] When SyncLoadContext receives a redirect response,

SyncLoadContext::OnReceivedRedirect() is called. It calls

FindClientHintsToRemove() to get `removed_headers`, and freezes

the ResourceRequestSender and signals

`redirect_or_response_event`.

- In the original thread:

[4] `redirect_or_response_event.Wait()` returns.

[5] URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() returns whether to follow

the redirect.

[6] If it returned true, post a task to the background to run

SyncLoadContext::FollowRedirect(). Otherwise post a task to run

SyncLoadContext::CancelRedirect.

- In the background thread:

[7] If SyncLoadContext::FollowRedirect() is called, it unfreezes the

ResourceRequestSender to follow the redirect. If SyncLoadContext::

CancelRedirect() is called, it cancels the request.



After this CL:

- In the the background thread:

[3] When SyncLoadContext receives a redirect response,

SyncLoadContext::OnReceivedRedirect() is called. It signals

`redirect_or_response_event`.

- In the original thread:

[4] `redirect_or_response_event.Wait()` returns.

[5] URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() is called with a

`follow_redirect_callback`. It calls ResourceLoader::

WillFollowRedirect() which calls FindClientHintsToRemove() to get

`removed_headers`, and returns whether to follow the redirect.

If ResourceLoader::WillFollowRedirect() returned true,

URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedRedirect() calls the

`follow_redirect_callback` synchronously.

[6] If the `follow_redirect_callback` was called, post a task to the

background to run SyncLoadContext::FollowRedirect(). Otherwise

post a task to run SyncLoadContext::CancelRedirect.

- In the background thread:

[7] If SyncLoadContext::FollowRedirect() is called, it calls

the `follow_redirect_callback_` to follow the redirect. If

SyncLoadContext::CancelRedirect() is called, it cancels the

request.



Thanks to this change, we don't need to freeze and unfreeze the

ResourceRequestSender in the background thread.

- In the original code, SyncLoadContext::OnReceivedRedirect() calls

ResourceRequestSender::Freeze(LoaderFreezeMode::kStrict), and

SyncLoadContext::FollowRedirect() calls

ResourceRequestSender::Freeze(LoaderFreezeMode::kNone). This is

intended to make the ResourceRequestSender wait until

FollowRedirect() is called from the original thread.

- But after this CL, ResourceRequestSender doesn't follow the redirect

until `follow_redirect_callback` is called. So we don't need to call

Freeze(kStrict) and Freeze(kNone) in SyncLoadContext.



Also, we can use the result of FindClientHintsToRemove() executed in the

original thread, because we can pass the `removed_headers` from the

original thread.

entry.title: [iOS] Move call to `settingsWillBeDismissed` in SettingsRootTableVC
entry.content:
Calling `settingsWillBeDismissed` in `willMoveToParentViewController`

was causing crashes as `willMoveToParentViewController` doesn't ensure

that we'll actually move to the parent view controller. For example,

initiating a back swipe on a view controller opened through Settings

without completing it would call `willMoveToParentViewController` even

if we don't actually go back to the previous page. This causes issues

because `settingsWillBeDismissed` is used to clear C++ objects, and so

those C++ objects would become null even if the view controller using

them could still be presented.



Moving the call to `settingsWillBeDismissed` to

`didMoveToParentViewController:` ensures that the C++ objects are

cleared when their view controller is no longer presented.



Context: https://chat.google.com/room/AAAAzEuhg8A/slcGEX9Y1Fw

entry.title: Update the profile when the active user has changed
entry.content:
There is a known issue when the user with OWNER ACCOUNT (the very first ACCOUNT that is logged in) logs in to the Chromebook, the profile is not re-created and they will continue to use the incognito sign-in profile. This causes crashes/misbehaviors for pref service or identity manager.



This issue is not witnessed for users who are NOT the OWNER ACCOUNT, e.g. the second and third account. For those users, their Profile instance is always created after their successful login, and that Profile instance correctly reflects their user data.



This CL fixes that issue by adding an Observer to the Mediator that listens to the "ActiveUserChanged" event. When the OWNER ACCOUNT user logs in, "ActiveUserChanged" is fired because the active user has switched from a null user (incognito profile) into a real OWNER user (real profile).



The method used in this CL is inspired by those applied in:

* Magnifier Manager: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/ash/accessibility/magnification_manager.cc;l=181-188



* System Clock:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/ash/system/system_clock.cc;l=83-90;drc=ea0d7cb33d730a591f481c84881dd8d009a6b948

entry.title: Speed up and re-enable deep dom serialization tests
entry.content:
Analogue of crrev.com/c/4755526.



For deep dom serialization tests, instead of waiting for each individual test to complete before starting the next one, we now eagerly start all the tests.



This reduces the test run time by a factor of 10× (from 7053 ms down to 668 ms) as observed on my workstation using these commands:



```

autoninja -C out/Default chrome blink_tests && \

third_party/blink/tools/run_web_tests.py -t Default http/tests/inspector-protocol/runtime/serialization-dom-types.js --timeout-ms 30000 && \

cat out/Default/layout-test-results/times_ms.json

```



Before:

```

{"http":{"tests":{"inspector-protocol":{"runtime":{"serialization-dom-types.js":7053}}}}}

```



After:

```

{"http":{"tests":{"inspector-protocol":{"runtime":{"serialization-dom-types.js":668}}}}}

```

entry.title: Move password manager only regexes out of Autofill code.
entry.content:
Short reasoning: The regexes are only used in password manager code, so

they should be declared there.



Long reasoning/why this is coming up now: Autofill's parsing logic is

moving to JSON-based, language dependent regex in a project called

pattern provider (see e.g. legacy_regex_patterns.json).

For the rollout, we want to ensure that the regexes in

autofill_regex_constants.h match the JSON file, before we ultimately

remove the JSON-based definitions from autofill_regex_constants.h.

While comparing the two files, it was noticed that

autofill_regex_constants.h contains password manager regexes - only some

of which have (unused) JSON-based definitions.



This CL removes the unused JSON-based definitions and moves password

manager regexes out of autofill_regex_constants.h. As a result (modulo

some minor exceptions addressed in follow-up CLs), this ensures that

autofill_regex_constants.h == legacy_regex_patterns.json.

entry.title: [BRP/clang-plugin] Bad Cast Detector: fix error positions
entry.content:
Given the following code, clang emits three |CastExpr|s.

```

(void*) static_cast(&v);

// ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ CStyleCastExpr 'void *'

// ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ CXXStaticCastExpr 'void *'

// ^~ ImplicitCastExpr 'void *'

```



I expected to have one "CXXStaticCastExpr " but there is an

extra |ImplicitCastExpr|.

As an effective cast occurs in |ImplicitCastExpr|, my plugin emits an

error under it. This CL fixes this behavior by emitting an error under

|CXXStaticCastExpr|.



This change does not turn non-error to error, nor error to non-error.

Just changes the location of `^~~~~` of the errors.





Context:

I'm not much interested in the error locations, but this matters to the

rewriter. I'm working on automatic `static_cast(obj)` ->

`base::unsafe_raw_ptr_static_cast(obj)` rewriter, and

it emits `static_cast(base::unsafe_raw_ptr_static_cast(obj))`

now. This change helps to fix the issue in the rewriter.

used to perform operations at some point in the future.



This will be used to determine whether Save to Photos settings can be

shown in Settings, which should be the case even if the service is not

"available" e.g. an operation is already ongoing but should not happen

if the service is not "supported".
